==English==
===Pronunciation===
*chĭp, /tʃɪp/, /<tt>tSIp</tt>/
*:[[Rhymes:English:-ɪp|Rhymes: -ɪp]]

===Noun===
'''chip''' (''plural'' '''[[chips]]''')

#A small [[piece]] broken from a larger piece of solid material.
#A [[token]] used in place of cash in [[gambling]].
#A [[damage]]d area of a surface where a chip has been broken off.
#:''This cup has a chip in it.''
#(''electronics'') A [[circuit]] fabricated in one piece on a small, thin [[substrate]].
#(''US'') A thin, crisp, baked piece of [[vegetable]], usually [[potato]].
#:''[[potato chip]]s''
#:''[[tortilla chip]]s''
#(''British'') A fried strip of [[potato]] of square or rectangular cross-section, similar to [[French fries]].
# (''sport'') A shot where the ball goes more upwards than a regular shot
<!--# (''slang'') [[feces]].  (''[[Cow chip]]s'')-->

====Synonyms====
*(''small piece broken off''): [[flake]]
*(''circuit''): [[IC]], [[integrated circuit]], [[silicon chip]]
*(''baked piece of vegetable''): [[crisp]] (''UK, Ireland'')
*(''fried strip of potato''): [[fries|fry]] (''US''), [[French fry|French fries]] (''US'')

====Translations====
*Finnish: [[siru]] (1,4), [[pelimerkki]] (2), [[särö]] (3), [[chippi]] (7)
*French: [[chip]] (5), [[frite]] (6), [[coche]] (7)
*Telugu: [[పెచ్చు]] (pecchu)

====See also====
*[[French fries]]
*[[fries]]
*[[potato wedge]]

===Transitive verb===
'''to chip''' ([[chips]], [[chipped]], [[chipping]])

#To [[break]] into small pieces.
#: ''The workers '''chipped''' the dead branches into mulch.''
#To [[break]] small pieces from.
#: ''Be careful not to '''chip''' the paint.''
#(''sport'') To play a shot where the ball goes predominately upwards rather than forwards
# (''automotive'') to upgrade an [[engine management system]], usually to increase power.

